tk3232
Sugar Land, TX4,269 contributions
If you love plants, flowers and various smart museums, then this is the place for you
Sep 2023 • Couples
In 1626, Louis XIII had his mind set to create a royal medicinal herb garden. Today, almost four hundred years later, the Jardin des Plantes' 75-acre botanical garden hosts a floral swirl of peonies, irises, roses, geraniums, and dahlias. The Jardin des Plantes is not only a botanical garden, it's also where you'll find Paris' oldest zoo, La Galerie Botanique, La Galerie de Mineralogie, the Grand Galerie de l'Evolution and the Natural History Museum. To visit all these museums we would need to have a lot of time in reserve, which we unfortunately didn't have and we limited ourselves to exploring and walking through the botanical garden, which pleased us with the flowering of roses and other plants in September.

But if you're visiting with children plan to spend at least half a day exploring including several play areas, zoo the Menagerie des Jardins des Plantes and some kid-friendly natural-science museums such as the Galerie des Enfants du Museum.
Visiting the park is free, open daily from 7:30 am - 8 pm. A visit to the park was part of our self-guided tour through the Latin Quarter, and can be combined with a visit to other attractions of Latin Quarter such as the Pantheon, Sorbonne or Mosquee de Paris, which are located within walking distance.
Written November 18, 2023

Benjamin
Paris, France299 contributions
A calm and relaxing moment in a busy day!
Dec 2022
We (a family of three, i.e., one adult and two young boys) spent an entire afternoon in the Jardin des Plantes to enjoy a less polluted moment within downtown Paris. The garden is nicely maintained all year long so that the walk is enjoyable anytime, and this holds both for when the weather is sunny, and when it is not. This is especially the case after a nice dinner in one of the small restaurants around.

When we were there (December 2022), we had the opportunity to enjoy a special exhibition about insects and their habits, in which quite a lot of information was provided through human-size representation located straight in the middle of the garden. After this visit and to escape the crowd (the garden is big, but it is additionally highly visited during school vacation), we went to the botanical garden that is also worth the detour. We learned quite a bit about botany and plants from different ecosystems.

In one line, I highly recommend the visit. However, please note that if you are interested in one of the numerous museums located inside the garden, please consider booking tickets in advance and targeting visits outside school vacation and week-end time. The crowd can be… a bit dense (which is the least I can write).
Written March 20, 2023
